 flourishing both depends upon and escapes the control of technologies. Faulty technology, oceanic and atmospheric turbulence, political corruption, and the inadequacies of basic science serve to foil governance over nature. Fish contends that what emerges is an ocean/culture—a flourishing ocean that is distinct from but exists alongside humanity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDrone aircraft in remote sensing. 0aInformation storage and retrieval systemsxMarine biology. 0aInformation storage and retrieval systems-Marine biology. 0aMarine biologyxRemote sensing. 0aMarine biologyxResearchxTechnological innovations. 0aMarine biology-Remote sensing. 0aMarine biology-Research-Technological innovations. 0aMarine sciencesxRemote sensing. 0aMarine sciencesxResearchxTechnological innovations. 0aMarine sciences-Remote sensing. 0aMarine sciences-Research-Technological innovations. 0aOceanographyxRemote sensing. 0aOceanographyxResearchxTechnological innovations. 0aOceanography-Remote sensing. 0aOceanography-Research-Technological innovations. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059011?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059011423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059011/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles